While I was updating an old app to use the new theming methods, I did the following using the command line:

1. Navigate to the `res/values/` directory for my app, and add a new file named `themes.xml`.
2. Navigate back one directory, to the `res/` directory and add a new directory called `values-night`.
3. Navigate into the newly created `res/values-night` directory and add a new file called `themes.xml`.

Now when I went back into Android Studio, it had automatically created the special `themes/` directory within the `res/values/` directory, which contains the two files - one for the light theme, and one for the dark theme.

You also need to update the following line in your manifest file to point to your theme files, rather than the `style.xml` file.

In your `AndroidManifest.xml` file, change this line from this:

    android:theme=&quot;@style/AppTheme&quot;&gt;

To this:

    android:theme=&quot;@style/Theme.YourAppName&quot;&gt;

**Theme.YouAppName** is the name that you add to the `themes.xml` files, as the style name, e.g:

    &lt;!-- Base application theme. --&gt;
    &lt;style name=&quot;Theme.YourAppName&quot; parent=&quot;Theme.AppCompat.DayNight.NoActionBar&quot;&gt;
        &lt;!-- Primary brand color. --&gt;
        &lt;item name=&quot;colorPrimary&quot;&gt;@color/colorPrimary&lt;/item&gt;
        &lt;item name=&quot;colorPrimaryVariant&quot;&gt;@color/colorPrimaryDark&lt;/item&gt;
        &lt;item name=&quot;colorSecondary&quot;&gt;@color/colorSecondary&lt;/item&gt;
    &lt;/style&gt;

I also posted this question over on the [Gradle forums][1]. I have copy/pasted the solution below.

